    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-28T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-28T15:00:00-05:00" n="955"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d955">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.6363/10–2144: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Braden</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-28T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >October 28, 1944—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>835. The fuel oil supply situation is such at present that it is possible to
                    approve a special allotment of 250,000 barrels to Cuba for consumption in 1944,
                    this special allotment to be used at the discretion of the Cuban officials for
                    the benefit of the national economy.</p>
                <p>The Essentials Requirements Committee refused to approve an allotment on a war
                    essential basis of fuel oil for the production of industrial alcohol (reurtel
                    917, October 21<note n="85" xml:id="d955fn85">Not printed.</note>). The
                    Committee did not wish to establish a precedent in this connection which might
                    be used by the Cubans in future negotiations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
